Correlation Coefficients

A quick explanation of how to properly use correlation coefficients when evaluating models

Introduction

The correlation coefficient (R2), which indicates the proportion of variation explained by an independant variable or model, can be calculated in more than one way. The goal of this vignette is to help clear up this confusion, with a few different examples.

# Load libraries toc_float: true
library(tidyverse); library(ggpmisc); library(ggpubr)

Load datasets

Data Set #1 = d1

  • Entry: 1 Genotype
  • Expt: 18 Site-years
  • Rep: 1-3 Reps per site-year
  • T_mean: Mean temperature
  • P_mean: Mean photoperiod
  • DTF: Days from sowing to flower
  • DTS: Days from sowing to swollen pod
  • RDTF: Rate of progress towards fowering
# Prep data
d1 <- read.csv("myData_1.csv") %>% 
  filter(!is.na(DTF), !is.na(DTS)) %>% # Remove any rows with missing data
  mutate(Expt = factor(Expt, levels = unique(Expt)),
         RDTF = 1 / DTF) # Rate of progress towards fowering

Basic Correlation

R2 can be calculated using the cor function which has method = "pearson" as the default.

# Calculate R^2 using the cor formula
cor(x = d1$DTF, y = d1$DTS, method = "pearson")^2
## [1] 0.9733758
# Switch x and y variables
cor(y = d1$DTF, x = d1$DTS, method = "pearson")^2
## [1] 0.9733758
# Simple correlation plot
mp <- ggplot(d1, aes(x = DTF, y = DTS)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) + 
  geom_point(aes(fill = Expt), size = 3, pch = 21, alpha = 0.7) + 
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  # Add R2 to plot
  stat_poly_eq(formula = y ~ x, parse = T, rr.digits = 7)
ggsave("RR_01.png", mp, width = 6, height = 4)

Figure 1: Correlation between DTF and DTS.

Interpretation: 97.33758% of variation in DTS is explained by DTF

Calculating R2

R2 can be manually calculated using the following formula to calculate Pearson’s r:

\(r=\frac{n\sum xy - (\sum x)(\sum y)}{\sqrt{(n\sum x^2 - (\sum x)^2)(n\sum y^2 - (\sum y)^2)}}\)

  • \(x\) = Independant variable
  • \(y\) = Dependant Variable
  • \(n\) = Number of observations

\(R^2=r^2\)

# Create R^2 function with Pearson's r formula
pearsonsR2 <- function(x, y) {
  n <- length(x)
  r_numerator <- n * sum(x*y) - sum(x) * sum(y)
  r_denominator <- sqrt( (n * sum(x^2) - sum(x)^2) * (n * sum(y^2) - sum(y)^2) )
  r <- r_numerator / r_denominator
  r^2
}
# Calculate R^2 using Pearson's formula
pearsonsR2(x = d1$DTF, y = d1$DTS)
## [1] 0.9733758
# Switch x and y variables
pearsonsR2(y = d1$DTF, x = d1$DTS)
## [1] 0.9733758

Visualizing R2

If you recall, the stat_poly_eq function included the option formula = y ~ x, which creates a linear regression of the x and y variables. Our R2 is a measure how how well the DTS data matches the predictions of DTS based on our DTF data.

# Perform linear regression
myModel <- lm(DTS ~ DTF, data = d1)
summary(myModel)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = DTS ~ DTF, data = d1)
## 
## Residuals:
##    Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
## -9.859 -2.938 -0.695  2.627 12.475 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 22.22217    1.93972   11.46 8.57e-15 ***
## DTF          0.96915    0.02416   40.11  < 2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.755 on 44 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9734, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9728 
## F-statistic:  1609 on 1 and 44 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
summary(myModel)$r.squared
## [1] 0.9733758
# Get predicted values and residual values from model
d1 <- d1 %>% mutate(Predicted_DTS = predict(myModel), 
                    Residuals_DTS = residuals(myModel) )

We can also calculate R2 by replacing DTF with with the Predicted_DTS values from our linear regression model.

# Calculate R^2 using Pearson's formula
pearsonsR2(x = d1$Predicted_DTS, y = d1$DTS)
## [1] 0.9733758
# Switch x and y variables
pearsonsR2(y = d1$Predicted_DTS, x = d1$DTS)
## [1] 0.9733758
# Calculate R^2 using cor function
cor(x = d1$Predicted_DTS, y = d1$DTS, method = "pearson")^2
## [1] 0.9733758
# Switch x and y variables
cor(y = d1$Predicted_DTS, x = d1$DTS, method = "pearson")^2
## [1] 0.9733758
# Plot
mp <- ggplot(d1, aes(x = DTF, y = DTS)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) + 
  geom_segment(aes(xend = DTF, yend = Predicted_DTS)) +
  geom_point(aes(fill = Expt, size = abs(Residuals_DTS)), pch = 21, alpha = 0.7) +
  stat_poly_eq(aes(label = paste(..eq.label.., ..rr.label.., sep = "*\",\"~~~")),
               formula = y ~ x, parse = T, rr.digits = 2) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
ggsave("RR_02.png", mp, width = 6, height = 4)

Figure 2: Correlation between DTF and DTS.

Another formula for calculating the R2 of a linear regression using Sum of Squares can help visualize this:

\(R^2=1-\frac{SS_{residuals}}{SS_{total}}=1-\frac{\sum (x-y)^2}{\sum (x-\bar{x})^2}\)

  • \(x\) = Observed value
  • \(y\) = Predicted value
  • \(\bar{x}=\frac{\sum x}{n}\) = Mean of observed values
# Create Sum of Squares R^2 function
modelR2 <- function(x, y) {
  1 - ( sum((x - y)^2) / sum((x - mean(x))^2) )
}
#
# Visulaize Sum of Squares
#
xx <- d1 %>% filter(Expt %in% c("Ro17","In17","It17","Ne17"), Rep == 2)
# Total Sum of Squares Plot
mp1 <- ggplot(xx, aes(x = DTF, y = DTS)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = mean(d1$DTS, na.rm = T)) +
  geom_text(x = 40, y = 100, size = 5, label = expression(italic(bar("y"))), parse = T) +
  geom_rect(alpha = 0.2, fill = "red",
            aes(xmin = DTF, xmax = DTF + (mean(d1$DTS, na.rm = T) - DTS), 
                ymin = DTS, ymax = mean(d1$DTS, na.rm = T))) +
  geom_point(size = 2) + 
  geom_point(data = d1, alpha = 0.2) +
  labs(title = "Total Sum of Squares")
# Residual Sum of Squares Plot
mp2 <- ggplot(xx, aes(x = DTF, y = DTS)) + 
  geom_smooth(data = d1, method = "lm", se = F, color = "black") +
  geom_text(x = 70, y = 100, size = 5, label = expression(italic("f")), parse = T) +
  geom_rect(alpha = 0.2, fill = "blue",
            aes(xmin = DTF, xmax = DTF - Residuals_DTS, 
                ymin = DTS, ymax = Predicted_DTS)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) + 
  geom_point(data = d1, alpha = 0.2) +
  labs(title = "Residual Sum of Squares")
# Appened
mp <- ggarrange(mp1, mp2, ncol = 2)
ggsave("RR_03.png", mp, width = 8, height = 4)

Figure 3: Visualization of (A) Total Sum of Squares and (B) Residual Sum of Squares.

In this case:

  • \(x\) = Observed value = DTS
  • \(y\) = Predicted value = Predicted_DTS
  • \(\bar{x}\) = Mean of observed values = mean(DTS, na.rm = T)
# Calculate R^2 using SS formula
modelR2(x = d1$DTS, y = d1$Predicted_DTS)
## [1] 0.9733758
# Swap x and y variables
modelR2(y = d1$DTS, x = d1$Predicted_DTS)
## [1] 0.9726475

Note: it is important to set DTS as the observed variable and Predicted_DTS as the predicted variable. This is becuase with the sum of squares model, our trendline has a slope = 1 and intercept = 0 (geom_abline), which is matched by lm(DTS~Predicted_DTS) but not lm(Predicted_DTS~DTS).

# Intercept = 0, Sploe = 1
round(lm(DTS~Predicted_DTS, data = d1)$coefficients, 3)
##   (Intercept) Predicted_DTS 
##             0             1
# Intercept != 0, Sploe != 1
round(lm(Predicted_DTS~DTS, data = d1)$coefficients, 3)
## (Intercept)         DTS 
##       2.523       0.973
# Plot
mp1 <- ggplot(d1, aes(y = DTS, x = Predicted_DTS)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, color = "red") + 
  geom_abline() +
  geom_point(aes(fill = Expt, size = abs(Residuals_DTS)), pch = 21, alpha = 0.7)
mp2 <- ggplot(d1, aes(x = DTS, y = Predicted_DTS)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ x, se = F, color = "red") + 
  geom_abline() + 
  geom_point(aes(fill = Expt, size = abs(Residuals_DTS)), pch = 21, alpha = 0.7)
mp <- ggarrange(mp1, mp2, ncol = 2, legend = "none")
ggsave("RR_04.png", mp, width = 8, height = 4)

Figure 4: Correlation between DTS and predicted DTS based on DTF.

Why is this important? Improper usage can lead to inncorrect interpretations. The first involved inncorrectly calculating R2 by swapping our observed and predciicted variables within the Sum of Squares formula. The second obvious example would be using the Sum of Squares formula without predictions vs. observations. E.g., if we calculate R2 using our modelR2 function with DTF vs DTS.

# Calculate R^2 using SS formula
modelR2(x = d1$DTF, y = d1$DTS)
## [1] 0.5022976
# Plot
mp1 <- ggplot(d1, aes(x = DTF, y = DTS)) +
  geom_abline() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) + 
  geom_segment(aes(xend = DTF, yend = Predicted_DTS)) +
  geom_point(aes(fill = Expt, size = abs(Residuals_DTS)), pch = 21, alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = substitute(paste(italic("R")^2, " = ", r2), 
         list(r2 = round(pearsonsR2(x = d1$DTF, y = d1$DTS), 3))))
mp2 <- ggplot(d1, aes(x = DTF, y = DTS)) +
  geom_abline() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) + 
  geom_segment(aes(xend = DTF, yend = DTF)) +
  geom_point(aes(fill = Expt, size = abs(Residuals_DTS)), pch = 21, alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = substitute(paste(italic("R")^2, " = ", r2), 
         list(r2 = round(modelR2(x = d1$DTF, y = d1$DTS), 3))))
# Append Plots
mp <- ggarrange(mp1, mp2, nrow= 1, ncol = 2, labels = c("A)", "B)"), legend = "none")
ggsave("RR_05.png", mp, width = 8, height = 4)

Figure 5: Correlation between DTF and DTS.

However, the more common mistake happens when evaluating the accuracy of a model. E.g.,:

# Plot
mp <- ggplot(d2, aes(x = Predicted_DTF, y = DTF)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) + 
  geom_abline() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", lty = 6, se = F) +
  facet_wrap(Expt~., scales = "free", ncol = 2) +
  stat_poly_eq(formula = y ~ x, parse = T, rr.digits = 7) +
  labs(title = "Incorrect usage of R^2")
ggsave("RR_06.png", mp, width = 8, height = 4)

Figure 6: Incorrect usage of R^2 to asses predictive capability of a model in two environments.

my_ggplot <- function(expt) {
  # Prep data
  xx <- d2 %>% filter(Expt == expt)
  xx <- xx %>%
    mutate(Trendline     =   predict(lm(DTF ~ Predicted_DTF, data = xx)))
  # Plot
  mp1 <- ggplot(xx, aes(x = Predicted_DTF, y = DTF)) + 
    geom_segment(aes(xend = Predicted_DTF, yend = Trendline), alpha = 0.5) +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + geom_abline() +
    labs(title = expt,
         subtitle = substitute(paste(italic("R")^2, " = ", r2), 
           list(r2 = round(pearsonsR2(x = xx$DTF, y = xx$Predicted_DTF), 3))))
  mp2 <- ggplot(xx, aes(x = Predicted_DTF, y = DTF)) + 
    geom_segment(aes(xend = Predicted_DTF, yend = Predicted_DTF), alpha = 0.5) +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + geom_abline() +
    labs(subtitle = substitute(paste(italic("R")^2, " = ", r2), 
           list(r2 = round(modelR2(x = xx$DTF, y = xx$Predicted_DTF), 3))))
  ggarrange(mp1, mp2, ncol = 2, align = "h")
}
# Ro17
mp <- my_ggplot("Ro17")
ggsave("RR_07.png", mp, width = 8, height = 4)

Figure 7: Incorrect and correct usage of R^2 to asses predictive capability of a model in two environments.

# Ro17
mp <- my_ggplot("Ne17")
ggsave("RR_08.png", mp, width = 8, height = 4)

Figure 8: Incorrect and correct usage of R^2 to asses predictive capability of a model in two environments.

Negative R2 values

Using Pearson’s formula R2 values will always fall between 0 and 1. However, when using the Sum of Squares formula (which has an intercept of 0), negative values can be aquired.

# Calculate R^2 for Ne17
xx <- d2 %>% filter(Expt == "Ne17")
modelR2(x = xx$DTF, y = xx$Predicted_DTF)
## [1] -2.865573

R^2 for Ne17 is < 0, What does this mean? and how do we interpret it?

R2 = 1 = regression is perfect, no errors

since,

\(R^2=1-\frac{SS_{residuals}}{SS_{total}}=1-\frac{0}{\sum (x-\bar{x})}=1\)

# Calculate R^2 of perfect regression
modelR2(x = xx$DTF, y = xx$DTF)
## [1] 1

R2 = 0 = regression is no better than using the mean

since,

\(y=\bar{x}\)

and,

\(R^2=1-\frac{SS_{residuals}}{SS_{total}}=1-\frac{\sum (x-\bar{x})}{\sum (x-\bar{x})}=1-1=0\)

# Prep data
xx <- xx %>% mutate(Mean_DTF = mean(DTF))
# Calculate R^2 with mean
modelR2(x = xx$DTF, y = xx$Mean_DTF)
## [1] 0

R2 < 0 = regression is worse than using the mean.

\(R^2=1-\frac{SS_{residuals}}{SS_{total}}=1-(>1)=(<0)\)

# Calculate the Sum of Squares for the residuals
sum((xx$DTF - xx$Predicted_DTF)^2)
## [1] 192250.6
# Calculate the total Sum of Squares
sum((xx$DTF - mean(xx$DTF))^2)
## [1] 49734.05

\(SS_{residuals} > SS_{total}\)

# Plot
mp1 <- ggplot(xx, aes(x = Predicted_DTF, y = DTF)) + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = mean(xx$DTF), color = "Red") +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = Predicted_DTF, yend = Mean_DTF), alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Total Sum of Squares",
       subtitle = round(sum((xx$DTF - mean(xx$DTF))^2)))
mp2 <- ggplot(xx, aes(x = Predicted_DTF, y = DTF)) + 
  geom_abline(color = "Blue") +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = Predicted_DTF, yend = Predicted_DTF), alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Residual Sum of Squares",
       subtitle = round(sum((xx$DTF - xx$Predicted_DTF)^2)))
mp <- ggarrange(mp1, mp2, ncol = 2)
ggsave("RR_09.png", mp, width = 8, height = 4)

Figure 9: Visualization of (A) Total Sum of Squares and (B) Residual Sum of Squares for Ne17.

RMSE

The The Root-Mean-Square Error (RMSE) is a measure of the differences between observed and predicted, or an average deviation of the predicted vs observed values.

\(RMSE=\frac{\sum (y-x)^2}{n}\)

  • \(x\) = Observed value
  • \(y\) = Predicted value
  • \(n\) = Number of observations
# Create RMSE function
modelRMSE <- function(x, y) {
  sqrt(sum((x-y)^2) / (length(x)))
}
# Calculate RMSE for Ro17
xx <- d2 %>% filter(Expt == "Ro17")
modelRMSE(xx$DTF, xx$Predicted_DTF)
## [1] 0.9455848
# Calculate RMSE for Ne17
xx <- d2 %>% filter(Expt == "Ne17")
modelRMSE(xx$DTF, xx$Predicted_DTF)
## [1] 24.35911

interpretation: the standard deviation of the unexplained variance in Ro17 is 0.95 and in Ne17 is 24.4.

Final Plots

Note: for easier interpretation, the x and y axis have been swapped, since overpredictions will be above the geom_abline and underpredictions below.

my_ggplot <- function(expt) {
  # Prep data
  xx <- d2 %>% filter(Expt == expt)
  r2 <- round(modelR2(x = xx$DTF, y = xx$Predicted_DTF), 3)
  rmse <- round(modelRMSE(x = xx$DTF, y = xx$Predicted_DTF), 1)
  mymin <- min(c(xx$DTF, xx$Predicted_DTF))
  mymax <- max(c(xx$DTF, xx$Predicted_DTF))
  # Plot
  ggplot(xx, aes(x = DTF, y = Predicted_DTF)) +
    geom_point(pch = 21, fill = "darkgreen", size = 2, alpha = 0.7) + 
    geom_abline() + 
    ylim(c(mymin, mymax)) +
    xlim(c(mymin, mymax)) +
    facet_grid(.~Expt) +
    labs(y = "Predicted DTF", x = "Observed DTF",
         title = substitute(
           paste(italic("R")^2, " = ", r2, " | ", italic("RMSE"), " = ", rmse), 
           list(r2 = r2, rmse = rmse)) )
}
mp <- my_ggplot("Ro17")
ggsave("RR_10.png", mp, width = 6, height = 4)

Figure 10: Correlation between Observed and predicted DTF in Ro17.

mp <- my_ggplot("Ne17")
ggsave("RR_11.png", mp, width = 6, height = 4)

Figure 11: Correlation between Observed and predicted DTF in Ne17.

Photothermal model

Next we will evaluate a Photothermal Model which describes the reciprical of DTF (RDTF) as a linear function of temperature and photoperiod:

\(\frac{1}{f}=a+b\overline{T}+c\overline{P}\)

  • \(f\) = Days from sowing to flower (DTF)
  • \(\overline{T}\) = Mean temperature (T_mean)
  • \(\overline{P}\) = Mean photoperiod (P_mean)
  • \(a,b,c\) = Genotype specific constants
# Perform linear regression
myModel <- lm(RDTF ~ T_mean + P_mean, data = d1)
summary(myModel)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = RDTF ~ T_mean + P_mean, data = d1)
## 
## Residuals:
##        Min         1Q     Median         3Q        Max 
## -0.0038514 -0.0005430  0.0002376  0.0006571  0.0038835 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -2.023e-02  1.547e-03 -13.074  < 2e-16 ***
## T_mean       6.502e-04  7.859e-05   8.274 1.95e-10 ***
## P_mean       2.007e-03  1.040e-04  19.292  < 2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.001642 on 43 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.931,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.9278 
## F-statistic: 290.1 on 2 and 43 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

In this case we now have multiple independant varables and cannot correlate RDTF with T_mean + P_mean using Pearson’s formula. Instead we will correlate RDTF with the Predicted_RDTF values that come from the model.

# Get predicted values and residual values from model
d1 <- d1 %>% mutate(Predicted_RDTF =     predict(myModel), 
                    Predicted_DTF  = 1 / predict(myModel),
                    Residuals_RDTF =     residuals(myModel),
                    Residuals_DTF = abs((1/DTF)-(1/Predicted_DTF)))
# Calculate R^2 using cor function
cor(d1$RDTF, d1$Predicted_RDTF)^2
## [1] 0.9310119
# Calculate R^2 using Pearson's formula
pearsonsR2(x = d1$RDTF, y = d1$Predicted_RDTF)
## [1] 0.9310119
# Calculate R^2 using SS formula
modelR2(x = d1$RDTF, y = d1$Predicted_RDTF)
## [1] 0.9310119
# Plot
mp <- ggplot(d1, aes(x = Predicted_RDTF, y = RDTF)) +
  geom_segment(aes(yend = Predicted_RDTF, xend = Predicted_RDTF)) +
  geom_point(aes(fill = Expt, size = abs(Residuals_RDTF)), pch = 21, alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_abline() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, lty = 6) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
ggsave("RR_12.png", mp, width = 8, height = 4)

Figure 12: Correlation between predicted RDTF and RDTF.

However, we are interested in DTF and not RDTF. Let see how R2 changes when we calculate it for DTF instead of RDTF.

# Calculate R^2 using cor function
cor(x = d1$DTF, y = d1$Predicted_DTF)^2
## [1] 0.8972014
# Calculate R^2 using Pearson's formula
pearsonsR2(x = d1$DTF, y = d1$Predicted_DTF)
## [1] 0.8972014
# Calculate R^2 using SS formula
modelR2(x = d1$DTF, y = d1$Predicted_DTF)
## [1] 0.8960016

Notice the how the values of R2 from cor or pearssonR2 and modelR2 do not match. Why is this occuring?

# Plot
mp <- ggplot(d1, aes(y = DTF, x = Predicted_DTF)) +
  geom_segment(aes(yend = Predicted_DTF, xend = Predicted_DTF)) +
  geom_point(aes(fill = Expt, size = abs(Residuals_DTF)), pch = 21, alpha = 0.7) + 
  geom_abline() + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, lty = 6) +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + 
  labs(title = substitute(paste(italic("R")^2, " = ", r2), 
         list(r2 = round(modelR2(x = d1$DTF, y = d1$Predicted_DTF), 3))))
ggsave("RR_13.png", mp, width = 6, height = 4)

Figure 13: Correlation between predicted DTF and DTF.

Now that we’ve transformed the data, the geom_abline and geom_smooth lines no longer perfectly overlap, which causes the slight difference in R2.

However, this still leaves open the questions of why geom_abline() and geom_smooth no longer overlap after transforming the data? Lets try and visualize this with test data.

# Prep data
xx <- data.frame(x = 1:10, y = 1:10 + 0.5) %>% 
  mutate(Residuals = abs(y-x))
SSt <- sum((xx$x - mean(xx$x))^2)
SSr <- sum((xx$x - xx$y)^2)
r2 <- round(1 - SSr / SSt, 4)
# Plot
mp1 <- ggplot(xx, aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_abline() + 
  geom_segment(aes(xend = x, yend = x)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = Residuals), alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = substitute(paste(italic("R")^2, " = 1 - (", SSr, "/",SSt, ") = ", r2 ), 
         list(SSr = SSr, SSt = SSt, r2 = r2)))
# Prep data
xx <- xx %>% mutate(Residuals = abs((1/y)-(1/x)))
SSt <- sum((1 / xx$x - mean(1 / xx$x))^2)
SSr <- sum((1 / xx$x - 1 / xx$y)^2)
r2 <- round(1 - SSr / SSt, 4)
# Plot
mp2 <- ggplot(xx, aes(x = 1 / x, y = 1 / y)) + 
  geom_abline() +
  geom_segment(aes(xend = 1 / x, yend = 1 / x)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = Residuals), alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = substitute(paste(italic("R")^2, " = 1 - (", SSr, "/",SSt, ") = ", r2 ), 
         list(SSr = round(SSr, 3), SSt = round(SSt, 3), r2 = r2)))
# Append Plots
mp <- ggarrange(mp1, mp2, ncol = 2, legend = "none")
ggsave("RR_14.png", mp, width = 8, height = 4)

Figure 14: Effect of data transformation on model residuals.

Visualizing the Photothermal model

x <- d1$T_mean
y <- d1$P_mean
z <- d1$RDTF
fit <- lm(z ~ x + y)
# Create PhotoThermal plane
fitpoints <- predict(fit)
grid.lines = 12
x.pred <- seq(min(x), max(x), length.out = grid.lines)
y.pred <- seq(min(y), max(y), length.out = grid.lines)
xy <- expand.grid(x = x.pred, y = y.pred)
z.pred <- matrix(predict(fit, newdata = xy), 
                 nrow = grid.lines, ncol = grid.lines)
# Plot with regression plane
png("RR_15.png", width = 600, height = 600)
par(mar=c(1.5, 2.5, 1.5, 0.5))
plot3D::scatter3D(x, y, z, pch = 18, cex = 2, zlim = c(0.005,0.03), 
  theta = 40, phi = 25, ticktype = "detailed", cex.lab = 1, cex.axis = 0.5,
  xlab = "Temperature", ylab = "Photoperiod", zlab = "1 / DTF",  
  surf = list(x = x.pred, y = y.pred, z = z.pred, col = "black", 
  facets = NA, fit = fitpoints), main = "PhotoThermal Model")
dev.off()
